In trying to trace through some external code (code is a JAR, but I have 
attached the source in the Properties of the project), the debugger displays 
the error message:
           Editor could not be initialized.
Looking at the .log, the error starts with the failure to load a class, as 
seen from this snippet:
           java.lang.ClassFormatError: com/bofa/esm/util/UtilityTestSuite 
(Illegal Field name "has inconsistent hierarchy")

The class file in question is a simple test suite file.  The code is:

/*
 * EJBTestServlet.java
 *
 * Created on September 19, 2002, 2:46 PM
 */
package com.bofa.esm.util;

import org.apache.cactus.*;
import junit.framework.*;
import com.bofa.esm.data.*;

/**
 *
 * @author  nbt86yz
 */
public class UtilityTestSuite extends ServletTestCase {
        
    public UtilityTestSuite(String name) {
        super(name);
    }
     
    public static void main(String[] theArgs) {
        junit.swingui.TestRunner.main(new String[] 
{UtilityTestSuite.class.getName()});
    }
 
    public static Test suite() {
        TestSuite suite =  new TestSuite();
        
        suite.addTest(TestEnvironmentMappings.suite());
        suite.addTest(TestTMRConfigurationBean.suite());        
        suite.addTest(TestDataAccessBean.suite());
        suite.addTest(TestEncryptDecryptDataBean.suite());
        
        return suite;
    }
    
}


As one can see, there is not much to it.  The code is compiled using an ant 
script and JDK build 1.4.2_05-b04.  The application itself is a J2EE 
application running in JBoss 3.2.5.

The interesting bit is that I am in no way tracing through the code that being 
flagged in the error, nor is this class being used in any capacity in the 
application itself, but yet the editor seems to feel obligated to trying to 
load the class.  Also interesting is that once this error happens, I can no 
longer open ANY java files at all, and switching to the Java view gives the 
error:
             An error has occured when activating this view
